<paragraph blockId="104.[189,1398,991,1158]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
This species is characterized by very long sparse hairs/bristles on the top of its leaves. It is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": de Candolle" authorityYear="1864" box="[306,453,1026,1052]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thomsonii">
<emphasis box="[306,453,1026,1052]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">B. thomsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as both are very hairy plants but 
<taxonomicName box="[834,990,1026,1052]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="limprichtii">
<emphasis box="[834,990,1026,1052]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">B. limprichtii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a more dentate leaf margin and longer sparser hairs on the upper surface. The species is not included above as no herbarium specimens have been seen, however, photographs from East and West Siang, Arunachal-Pradesh (
<bibRefCitation author="Morris R." box="[1225,1390,1096,1123]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" pagination="214 - 218" refId="ref56580" refString="Morris R. 2010 b. A ' new' Begonia species from India. The Begonian 77: 214 - 218." type="journal article" year="2010">
<emphasis box="[1225,1306,1097,1122]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Morris</emphasis>
2010b
</bibRefCitation>
) are potential records for the study area.
</paragraph>
